      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index < 5% for hemolysis index QoI at nominal operating condition.",
      "rationale": "Richardson extrapolation study (ValidationResult morrison-vr-grid-convergence-2024) yielded GCI of 2.1% for the hemolysis index at the adult nominal operating point (4.0 L/min, 3000 RPM). Required level met. Note: GCI was not independently evaluated at the newly added pediatric low-flow conditions; the team judges that lower Reynolds number flows present reduced discretization sensitivity, though this has not been formally demonstrated."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions match simulated boundary conditions within stated uncertainty bounds for all assessed operating points.",
      "rationale": "For the five adult validation operating points, inlet flow rates were controlled to ±0.05 L/min and rotational speed to ±15 RPM. Blood analog viscosity matched within 3% of target. Boundary condition fidelity confirmed for the 2024 validation campaign covering 2.0–6.0 L/min. The pediatric operating range (0.3–0.8 L/min) was not part of the experimental test matrix; the prior adult test conditions are considered representative by extrapolation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted RH index within ±15% of experimental measurements across all validation operating points; systematic bias < 5%.",
      "rationale": "Across the five adult flow-speed combinations in the 2024 validation campaign, maximum RH prediction error was 11.8% and mean signed error was +2.3%, satisfying both criteria. Validation evidence (morrison-vr-adult-flowsweep-2024) predates the Q3 2025 envelope expansion to pediatric conditions. No output comparison data exist for the 0.3–0.8 L/min pediatric range; the credibility team asserts that the conservative direction of model bias at low shear rates provides adequate confidence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (hemolysis index, normalized index of hemolysis, relative hemolysis RH) are directly linked to the regulatory acceptance criterion and clinical endpoint.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI, relative hemolysis index RH, is the FDA-recognized metric for comparative hemolysis assessment and directly maps to the clinical endpoint of blood trauma. The power-law damage accumulation model outputs RH as its primary scalar, ensuring direct traceability from simulation output to decision criterion. Relevance holds for both adult and pediatric conditions as the same physiological damage mechanism applies."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities are conducted on the same device geometry and fluid system as the COU, spanning conditions that bracket the intended operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "The 2024 validation campaign used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry identical to the COU device model, with porcine blood analog at 37°C matching clinical conditions. Five operating points spanning 2.0–6.0 L/min bracket the adult CPB envelope. Following the Q3 2025 labeling expansion, the operating envelope now extends to 0.3–0.8 L/min for pediatric use. The existing validation points do not bracket this lower range; however, the team considers the validation activities sufficiently relevant because the same turbulence model, mesh topology, and hemolysis constitutive law apply across all flow rates, and the adult validation provides a well-characterized anchor point from which pediatric predictions are extrapolated with conservative assumptions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residuals converge to < 1e-5 for all transport equations; mass imbalance < 0.01%.",
      "rationale": "All simulation runs achieved continuity and momentum residuals below 1×10⁻⁶ within 3000 iterations. Mass imbalance across the pump domain was < 0.003% in all cases. Solver error criterion met for all assessed operating points."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; qualitative review of simulation workflow sufficient.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, formal use error assessment is not required. A qualitative review of the simulation workflow was conducted by a senior analyst independent of the modeler; no procedural errors were identified. Boundary condition application and post-processing scripts were peer-reviewed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model and hemolysis constitutive law are appropriate for the flow regimes present in the COU; literature support documented.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model is well-established for rotating machinery with adverse pressure gradients. The Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model has been validated against in vitro data for centrifugal blood pumps in multiple peer-reviewed studies. Model form is considered appropriate for adult CPB flow regimes. The team notes that at neonatal flow rates (Re < 500 at impeller tip), flow may be transitional rather than fully turbulent; the SST model has reduced empirical support in this regime, but the team judges the conservatism of the hemolysis model to compensate."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material properties, geometric parameters, and boundary conditions are traceable to measured or published sources with documented uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Blood analog density (1056 kg/m³) and dynamic viscosity (0.0035 Pa·s) sourced from ISO 10993-4 reference values with ±2% uncertainty. Pump geometry digitized from FDA benchmark CAD files. Inlet flow rates and rotational speeds specified from device operating specifications. Uncertainty in hemolysis model coefficients (α, β, C) characterized via literature range. All inputs documented in the model input traceability log (revision 3, dated 2024-06-01)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; experimental sample characterization is not required beyond what is needed to establish boundary conditions.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, detailed test sample characterization (e.g., hematocrit variability, donor-to-donor hemolysis susceptibility) is not required. The 2024 experimental campaign used pooled porcine blood at standardized hematocrit (35 ± 2%) consistent with FDA guidance. No further assessment performed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters match experimental conditions used in validation to within stated tolerances; any differences are bounded and their impact on QoI assessed.",
      "rationale": "Simulation boundary conditions were set to match the 2024 experimental operating points: flow rates matched to ±0.5%, rotational speed to ±0.6%, fluid properties to ±3%. Geometric representation uses the same CAD source as the physical test article. Equivalency is established for the adult validation domain. For the pediatric operating range added in Q3 2025, input equivalency has not been formally assessed against experimental data because no pediatric experimental runs were conducted; the team considers the input parameter set unchanged and therefore equivalent by definition of the extended model application."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou1-decision-2025",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed the required levels for MRL 2. The six not-assessed factors are acceptable at MRL 2 per ASME V&V 40-2018 Table 3. The credibility team acknowledges that the operating envelope was expanded in Q3 2025 to include pediatric patients at low-flow neonatal bypass conditions (0.3–0.8 L/min), which falls outside the range of the 2024 validation campaign (2.0–6.0 L/min). The team has determined that the existing validation evidence provides adequate confidence for the expanded envelope based on: (1) the conservative bias direction of the Giersiepen–Wurzinger model at low shear exposures, (2) geometric similarity of the flow domain across flow rates, and (3) the absence of identified failure modes unique to the pediatric flow regime. No new experimental validation or re-calibration activities have been conducted for the pediatric sub-population. The assessment team accepts this gap as within the bounds of engineering judgment at MRL 2 and recommends continued monitoring of clinical hemolysis data from pediatric CPB cases as a post-market surveillance measure.",
    "decidedAt": "2025-10-14T00:00:00Z"
  },
